ÎÎµÏ. Î¹ÎµÎ. â CHAP. XV.

P. 26, 1.277ââNow appoint for yourselves,â ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î®ÏÎ±ÏÎµ
Î¿á½Î½ á¼Î±Ï
ÏÎ¿á¿Ï] Î§ÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î­Ï occurs only twice in the New
Testament (Acts xiv.23; 2 Cor. viii.19), and, in both places,
means simply to âappoint.â Josephus uses the word in the
same sense in Ant. xiii.2, 2, where Alexander Balas, the
pretended son of Antiochus Epiphanes, âappointsâ Jonathan
High Priest. The same meaning appears in Ant. vii 9, 3;
vii. 11, 1. In ant. vi. 5, 4, however, the noun ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î¯Î± is
used of the coronation of Saul. In Josephus, accordingly, the
prevailing sense of ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î­Ï is to âappoint.â This is the
meaning of the word also in the Epistles of Ignatius (about
115 a.d.). See Philadelphians, Chap. 10; SmyrnÃ¦ns, Chap. 11;
Polycarp, Chap. 7.

But in the âApostolic Canons,â I. and II., and in the
âApostolic Constitutions,â viii. 4, 5, ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î­Ï means
to âordain.â This represents the usage of the third century,
as the New Testament, Josephus, and Ignatius represent
the usage of the first and second centuries.

Now, it is noteworthy, that in the âApostolic Constitutions,â
vii. 31 (the section corresponding to the passage before us),
the word employed is not ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î­Ï, which then meant
âordain,â but ÏÏÎ¿ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¯Î¶Î¿Î¼Î±Î¹, a new usage having obtained.
In this fifteenth chapter of the âTeaching,â ÏÎµÎ¹ÏÎ¿ÏÎ¿Î½Î­Ï is
employed, evidently, in its original sense of âappoint.â This
indicates the high antiquity of the document, antedating by
decades, if not by a whole century, the âApostolic Canonsâ
and the âApostolic Constitutions.â

As for the officers to be âappointed,â only Bishops and
Deacons are mentioned. By Bishops must, of course, be
meant Presbyters, or Elders. There is no sign of a Bishop
as distinguished from a Presbyter; nor of a Ruling Elder as
distinguished from a Teaching Elder; and, apparently, there
was in each congregation a plurality both of Bishops (or
Elders) and Deacons.

ÎÎµÏ. Î¹ÏÎ. â CHAP. XVI.

The document concludes with a vision of the Lord coming
upon the clouds of heaven, and all the saints with him. The
resurrection is of the dead, Î½ÎµÎºÏá¿¶Î½, though ânot of all the
dead.â Not a word is said of any second resurrection. If there
is to be a second resurrections, it is only implied. Of course,
no interval is indicated. Premillennarianism, accordingly, is
not directly, perhaps not even indirectly, taught. Following
the lead of the New Testament, as in Matt. xxiv. 31,
and in 1 Thess. iv. 13-18, our document may, after all,
only be emphasizing the resurrection of the righteous.

